README.md
     9ŌåÆ# Mitt
    11ŌåÆ> Tiny 200b functional event emitter / pubsub.
    12ŌåÆ
    13ŌåÆ-   **Microscopic:** weighs less than 200 bytes gzipped
    14ŌåÆ-   **Useful:** a wildcard `"*"` event type listens to all events
    15ŌåÆ-   **Familiar:** same names & ideas as [Node's EventEmitter](https://nodejs.org/api/events.html#events_class_eventemitter)
    16ŌåÆ-   **Functional:** methods don't rely on `this`
    17ŌåÆ-   **Great Name:** somehow [mitt](https://npm.im/mitt) wasn't taken
    18ŌåÆ
    19ŌåÆMitt was made for the browser, but works in any JavaScript runtime. It has no dependencies and supports IE9+.
    20ŌåÆ
    21ŌåÆ## Table of Contents
    23ŌåÆ-   [Install](#install)
    24ŌåÆ-   [Usage](#usage)
    25ŌåÆ-   [Examples & Demos](#examples--demos)
    26ŌåÆ-   [API](#api)
    27ŌåÆ-   [Contribute](#contribute)
    28ŌåÆ-   [License](#license)
    29ŌåÆ
    30ŌåÆ## Install
    32ŌåÆThis project uses [node](http://nodejs.org) and [npm](https://npmjs.com). Go check them out if you don't have them locally installed.
    33ŌåÆ
    34ŌåÆ```sh
    35ŌåÆ$ npm install --save mitt
    36ŌåÆ```
    37ŌåÆ
    38ŌåÆThen with a module bundler like [rollup](http://rollupjs.org/) or [webpack](https://webpack.js.org/), use as you would anything else:
    39ŌåÆ
    40ŌåÆ```javascript
    41ŌåÆ// using ES6 modules
    42ŌåÆimport mitt from 'mitt'
    43ŌåÆ
    44ŌåÆ// using CommonJS modules
    45ŌåÆvar mitt = require('mitt')
    46ŌåÆ```
    47ŌåÆ
    48ŌåÆThe [UMD](https://github.com/umdjs/umd) build is also available on [unpkg](https://unpkg.com):
    49ŌåÆ
    50ŌåÆ```html
    51ŌåÆ<script src="https://unpkg.com/mitt/dist/mitt.umd.js"></script>
    52ŌåÆ```
    53ŌåÆ
    54ŌåÆYou can find the library on `window.mitt`.
    55ŌåÆ
    56ŌåÆ## Usage
    58ŌåÆ```js
    59ŌåÆimport mitt from 'mitt'
    60ŌåÆ
    61ŌåÆconst emitter = mitt()
    62ŌåÆ
    63ŌåÆ// listen to an event
    64ŌåÆemitter.on('foo', e => console.log('foo', e) )
    65ŌåÆ
    66ŌåÆ// listen to all events
    67ŌåÆemitter.on('*', (type, e) => console.log(type, e) )
    68ŌåÆ
    69ŌåÆ// fire an event
    70ŌåÆemitter.emit('foo', { a: 'b' })
    71ŌåÆ
    72ŌåÆ// clearing all events
    73ŌåÆemitter.all.clear()
    74ŌåÆ
    75ŌåÆ// working with handler references:
    76ŌåÆfunction onFoo() {}
    77ŌåÆemitter.on('foo', onFoo)   // listen
    78ŌåÆemitter.off('foo', onFoo)  // unlisten
    79ŌåÆ```
    80ŌåÆ
    81ŌåÆ### Typescript
    83ŌåÆSet `"strict": true` in your tsconfig.json to get improved type inference for `mitt` instance methods.
    84ŌåÆ
    85ŌåÆ```ts
    86ŌåÆimport mitt from 'mitt';
    87ŌåÆ
    88ŌåÆtype Events = {
    89ŌåÆ  foo: string;
    90ŌåÆ  bar?: number;
    91ŌåÆ};
    92ŌåÆ
    93ŌåÆconst emitter = mitt<Events>(); // inferred as Emitter<Events>
    94ŌåÆ
    95ŌåÆemitter.on('foo', (e) => {}); // 'e' has inferred type 'string'
    96ŌåÆ
    97ŌåÆemitter.emit('foo', 42); // Error: Argument of type 'number' is not assignable to parameter of type 'string'. (2345)
    98ŌåÆ```
    99ŌåÆ
   100ŌåÆAlternatively, you can use the provided `Emitter` type:
   101ŌåÆ
   102ŌåÆ```ts
   103ŌåÆimport mitt, { Emitter } from 'mitt';
   104ŌåÆ
   105ŌåÆtype Events = {
   106ŌåÆ  foo: string;
   107ŌåÆ  bar?: number;
   108ŌåÆ};
   109ŌåÆ
   110ŌåÆconst emitter: Emitter<Events> = mitt<Events>();
   111ŌåÆ```
